When I do the following, Hibernate returns an object of type Basket, which has a List<Kiwi> in it, but unlike the one I persisted, it only has one element in it instead of two.:
List<Basket> Baskets = HibernateUtil.getSessionFactory().openSession().createSelectionQuery("FROM Basket", Basket.class).getResultList();

Concisely state a sequence of things I could be doing wrong and how to fix those issues.

To access the List<Kiwi> eagerly without changing Hibernate's annotations from lazy, you can use a fetch join in your HQL or Criteria query. This will fetch the associated Kiwi objects along with the Basket objects in a single database query. Here's an example:

HQL:

```java
List<Basket> baskets = session.createQuery("SELECT b FROM Basket b JOIN FETCH b.kiwis", Basket.class).getResultList();
```

Criteria:

```java
CriteriaBuilder cb = session.getCriteriaBuilder();
CriteriaQuery<Basket> cq = cb.createQuery(Basket.class);
Root<Basket> root = cq.from(Basket.class);
root.fetch("kiwis", JoinType.LEFT);
List<Basket> baskets = session.createQuery(cq).getResultList();
```

By using fetch join, you can eagerly load the List<Kiwi> property while keeping the lazy loading configuration intact.

List<Basket> Baskets = HibernateUtil.getSessionFactory().openSession().createSelectionQuery("SELECT a FROM Basket a LEFT JOIN FETCH Kiwi b ON a.BasketUuid = b.BasketUuid", Basket.class).getResultList();

yields

Could not resolve attribute 'BasketUuid' of 'com.mycompany.myapp.Kiwi' [SELECT a FROM Basket a LEFT JOIN FETCH Kiwi b ON a.BasketUuid = b.BasketUuid]

To eagerly fetch the List<Kiwi> along with other fields in the Basket entity using a Session object without explicitly writing a query, you can utilize Hibernate's fetch profile feature. Here's a concise example:

1. Define a fetch profile in your mapping file or with annotations:

```java
@Entity
@FetchProfile(name = "basketWithKiwis", fetchOverrides = {
    @FetchProfile.FetchOverride(entity = Basket.class, association = "kiwis", mode = FetchMode.JOIN)
})
public class Basket {
    // ...
}
```

2. Enable the fetch profile on the SessionFactory:

```java
Session session = HibernateUtil.getSessionFactory().openSession();
session.enableFetchProfile("basketWithKiwis");
```

3. Retrieve the Basket entity:

```java
List<Basket> baskets = session.createQuery("FROM Basket", Basket.class).getResultList();
```

By enabling the fetch profile "basketWithKiwis" and setting the association "kiwis" to use FetchMode.JOIN, Hibernate will eagerly fetch the List<Kiwi> along with other fields in the Basket entity during the query execution, without the need for an explicitly written query.
